2017 vs. 2016
Alaska reported earnings of $1,466 million in 2017, compared with earnings of $319 million in 2016. The increase in earnings was
mainly due to an $892 million tax benefit from the revaluation of allocated U.S. deferred taxes at a lower federal statutory rate, in
accordance with the Tax Legislation. Earnings were additionally improved due to higher crude oil prices in 2017. The earnings
increase was partly offset by a $110 million after-tax impairment charge for the associated properties, plants and equipment of our
small interest in the Point Thomson unit.
Average production increased 2 percent in 2017 compared with 2016, as the impact of normal field decline was more than offset by
well performance in the Western North Slope, Greater Prudhoe and Greater Kuparuk areas and lower unplanned downtime.
